I looked into this a little more. It seems that there are only a very few references to the library in _the code_:
```
enterprise/tomcat5/src/org/netbeans/modules/tomcat5/deploy/TomcatManagerImpl.java:import com.sun.org.apache.xerces.internal.impl.dv.util.Base64;
enterprise/web.core/src/org/netbeans/modules/web/wizards/TagInfoPanel.java:        return org.apache.xerces.util.XMLChar.isValidNCName(name);
enterprise/web.core/src/org/netbeans/modules/web/wizards/targetpanel/providers/TagTargetPanelProvider.java:        return org.apache.xerces.util.XMLChar.isValidNCName(name);

......

ide/xml.tax/lib/src/org/netbeans/tax/io/XNIBuilder.java:import org.apache.xerces.xni.*;
ide/xml.tax/lib/src/org/netbeans/tax/io/XNIBuilder.java:import org.apache.xerces.xni.parser.XMLDTDSource;
ide/xml.tax/lib/src/org/netbeans/tax/io/XNIBuilder.java:import org.apache.xerces.xni.parser.XMLDTDContentModelSource;
ide/xml.tax/lib/src/org/netbeans/tax/io/XNIBuilder.java:import org.apache.xerces.xni.parser.XMLDocumentSource;
ide/xml.tax/lib/src/org/netbeans/tax/io/XNIBuilder.java:import org.apache.xerces.parsers.*;
ide/xml.tax/src/org/netbeans/modules/xml/tax/parser/ParserLoader.java:    private static final String PARSER_PACKAGE = "org.apache.xerces";  // NOI18N
ide/xml.tax/src/org/netbeans/modules/xml/tax/parser/ParserLoader.java:    private static final String XERCES_ARCHIVE = "modules/autoload/ext/xerces2.jar"; // NOI18N
ide/xml.tax/src/org/netbeans/modules/xml/tax/parser/ParserLoader.java:        Class apache = me.loadClass("org.apache.xerces.util.QName"); // NOI18N
ide/html.validation/src/org/netbeans/modules/html/validation/NbValidationTransaction.java:    //xerces's default locator returns slightly shifted positions for character content
```

and from testing, it would seem that **we do not need Xerces at all** except perhaps those few XNI utilities and the TAX implementation. The utilities can be easily changed, TAX ... who knows what purpose does the TAX library serve these days - couldn't it be replaced by plain DOM in the codebase ?

@jtulach how to handle this compatibly ? Application developers may rely on having *working* Xerces distributed as a module; at the same time, NetBeans IDE does not really need (most of) it.

Also I cite below the comment from our (JetBrain) legal department about iCLA.

The individual contribution agreements (CLAs) should be modified to reflect that they cover only your contributions to the NetBeans plugin project, not all other contributions you may have made or might make in the future. Apache should be able to narrow it down easily but if not we can help them with the wording provided that we have an editable version of their documentation.

@ebarboni So you or somebody other from Apache could either modify iCLA this way yourself or provide an editable version for us.
